properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant snowfall expected overnight through Wednesday. Snow will begin overnight before spreading northeastward to James Bay on Wednesday morning. Snow will gradually end from west to east on Thursday. Total snowfall amounts of 15 to 25 cm are expected by Thursday afternoon. Locally higher amounts in excess of 30 cm will be possible. Driving conditions will quickly deteriorate overnight and into Wednesday morning as the snow begins. Motorists should consider changing travel plans accordingly. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Fog Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Pockets of dense fog have developed this evening significantly reducing visibility. Fog combined with freezing temperatures will produce locally icy conditions on the roads. The fog patches will dissipate overnight or Wednesday morning. ### Visibility may be significantly and suddenly reduced to near zero. Weather in the mountains can change suddenly resulting in hazardous driving conditions. Fog advisories are issued when near zero visibilities in fog are expected or occurring. Road conditions are available at www.drivebc.ca. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Extreme wind chills near minus 45 will develop tonight and persist into Wednesday morning. Below normal temperatures will continue through Wednesday and Wednesday night. ### Extreme cold puts everyone at risk. Risks are greater for young children, older adults, people with chronic illnesses, people working or exercising outdoors, and those without proper shelter. Watch for cold related symptoms: shortness of breath, chest pain, muscle pain and weakness, numbness and colour change in fingers and toes. For more information on cold and your health, visit Manitoba Health at https://www.gov.mb.ca/health/publichealth/environmentalhealth/cold.html or call Health Links - Info Santé at 204-788-8200 or toll-free at 1-888-315-9257. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to MBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.

properties.Title: Blowing Snow Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Poor visibility in snow and blowing snow is expected or occurring in some locations. Total snowfall: 2 to 4 cm in Nain, near 10 cm in Natuashish. Maximum wind gusts: northwesterly 100 km/h. Time span: tonight. Remarks: Fresh snowfall will combine with strong northwesterly winds tonight to produce poor visibility in blowing snow, especially in the Natuashish area. Conditions are expected to improve slightly on Wednesday morning as the snow tapers off. Blowing snow advisories are issued when winds are expected to create blowing snow giving poor visibility to 800 metres or less for at least 3 hours. properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow will continue over most of southern Manitoba tonight. Storm total snowfall will be between 10 to 25 cm by Wednesday morning. A strong low pressure system continues to track southeastward across the northern US bringing heavy snow, strong winds, and blowing snow to southern Manitoba tonight . A swath of 15 to 25 cm is likely north of the Trans-Canada and Yellowhead Highways. Winnipeg and areas between the Trans-Canada and the international border should expect a snow total of 5 to 10 cm. Poor visibilities will occur in snow and blowing blowing snow. Conditions have inproved over the Parklands area. The snow will ease through the rest of southern Manitoba overnight or early Wednesday morning as the weather system continues towards the Great Lakes. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become difficult to navigate due to accumulating snow. Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Visibility will be suddenly reduced to near zero at times in heavy snow and blowing snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to MBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A significant winter storm is expected tonight through Wednesday. Snow will begin for locations near Lake Nipigon this evening and reach the Geraldton area overnight. Snow will gradually taper to flurries from west to east on Thursday. Total snowfall amounts of 25 to 35 cm are expected by Thursday afternoon. Total accumulations of up to 50 cm locally are possible. Snow may mix with rain along the shoreline of Lake Superior on Wednesday morning and into early Wednesday afternoon as temperatures briefly rise above the freezing mark. As a result, lesser snowfall accumulations are anticipated immediately along the lake shore. Brisk northerly winds gusting 40 to 50 km/h on Wednesday and into Thursday will result in localized blowing snow over exposed areas. Driving conditions will quickly deteriorate tonight as the snow begins. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become difficult to navigate due to accumulating snow. properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Winter storm over southern Saskatchewan ending tonight. Storm total snowfall will be between 10 to 25 cm. A strong low pressure system will track along the International border bringing heavy snow to most of southern Saskatchewan today and into the evening. A total of 15 to 25 cm is expected through this evening, generally between the Trans-Canada and Yellowhead Highways. Very poor visibilities at times in snow and blowing snow will occur. The snow has eased along the Alberta boundary. Likewise, the snow is also easing from the north in the Outlook, Humbolt, and Kamsack regions and will end completely early this evening. The snow will end in the remaining regions later this evening. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become difficult to navigate due to accumulating snow. properties.Summary:
Description: Significant snowfall tonight into Wednesday. Snow will become heavy at times this evening. Total snowfall amounts of 10 to 15 cm are expected by Wednesday evening. Snow may become mixed with freezing drizzle tonight. Brisk northerly winds gusting 40 to 50 km/h on Wednesday will result in localized blowing snow over exposed areas. Driving conditions will quickly deteriorate this afternoon as the snow begins. Motorists should consider changing travel plans accordingly. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. properties.Summary:
Description: Significant snowfall is expected tonight into Wednesday. Snow will become heavy at times tonight. Total snowfall amounts of 10 to 20 cm are expected by Thursday morning. properties.Summary:

properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Mainly clear skies tonight will cause cold temperatures near -35 with light winds giving extreme windchills of minus 40. Temperatures will warm through the day Wednesday bringing an end to the extreme wind chill values. ### Extreme cold puts everyone at risk. Watch for cold related symptoms: shortness of breath, chest pain, muscle pain and weakness, numbness and colour change in fingers and toes. Extreme cold warnings are issued when very cold temperatures or wind chill creates an elevated risk to health such as frost bite and hypothermia. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ABstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ABStorm.
